ownedComment.body: AML Object Model

Archetype Package Overview

Archetypes are a mechanism for constraining information represented in an abstract, general reference model to specific domains and use cases. They remove from the reference model the need for semantic specificity, and this decoupling allows the reference model to be relatively stable and generally applicable, while the specific and multiform specification of rules constraining information in a domain is manifest in archetypes.

Since each archetype constitutes an encapsulation of limited a set of data elements pertaining to a specific topic, it is of a manageable, limited size, and has a clear boundary. For example an ‘Apgar result’ archetype of the openEHR reference model class OBSERVATION contains the data elements relevant to Apgar score of a newborn, while a ‘blood pressure measurement’ archetype contains data elements relevant to the result and measurement of blood pressure. Archetypes are assembled by templates to form structures used in computational systems, such as document definitions, message definitions and so on.

The Archetype meta-model describes a design for assembling constraints into archetypes and specifying how they refer to the reference model features that they constrain. It is designed to be as agnostic as possible as to the underlying reference model, but there are certain characteristics that must be assumed to exist in the reference model in order for a constraint to refer to it in a predictable manner. The Reference Metamodel package describes the subset of the UML Modeling Language that an archetype constraint can be applied.

AML constraints may then be implemented in various implementable forms, including such constraint languages as the openEHR Archetype Definition Language (ADL), MDHT, etc.

The Archetype model

Every Archetype is identified a unique identifier of type ArchetypeId. While the structure and format of the ArchetypeId are not specified in this document, many AML communities have found it beneficial to describe a formal structure for the identifier that allows it to simultaneously be human readable as well as being decomposable into a number of identifying properties which can be combined or parsed in various ways for use in different circumstances. Archetypes carry a reference to the specific version of the AML specification that was used in their creation, an optional version identifier that can be used to the state of the archetype in an externally defined work flow and an optional terminology code that provides the ability to name and describe the archetype in a multilingual environment.

Every Archetype is a collection of constraints that are apply to instances of one or more classes and types target UML Reference Model. The ReferenceModelReference class identifies the model, package, release/version of the Reference Model that contains the class to which the specific archetype definition applies. The details of how the targetReferenceModel aligns with a reference model instance are described in Object Constraint References section.

An Archetype is a software artifact and, as such, needs to be accompanied by shared metadata and workflow models. While the structure and content of these models are outside the scope of this RFP response, the AuthoredResource class represents a minimal scaffolding upon which a richer model could be anchored.

The core of an archetype is its definition, a nested collection of constraints against the underlying reference model. Every archetype includes a "definition" in the form of a constraint on a specific class within a UML Reference Model. This constraint may be as simple as assigning a terminology code to the class or may involve complex traversals that constrain properties and associations that the class participates in as well as the properties and associations of the types those properties reference recursively. See the Constraint Model package for further details on constraint definitions.

An archetype also contains an instance of an ArchetypeTerminology, which supplies the semantics of the constraints, which include multilingual names and descriptions for the various constraint artifacts as well as describing the possible values for enumerations and coded terms. These possible values can either be stated within the archetype or be references to an external terminological resource. The terminology is what allows Archetypes to be natural language- and terminology-neutral. See the Terminology Binding package for further details.

An archetype may contain a set of rules for specifying constraints on relationships among different elements within the archetype. The definition--the primary method for defining constraints--is composed of primitive constraints assembled into complex objects, and can control individual values, but constraints involving disjoint values, such as a constraint that ‘systolic pressure should be less than diastolic pressure’ in a blood pressure measurement Archetype, require a syntax that can address multiple elements at once. This is the function of the rules element. See the Rules package for further details.

Archetype references

As shown in the following diagram, a given Archetype may reference several other Archetypes. These references can take one of two forms:

First, specialization permits the reuse of common constraints in a family of related archetypes.

An archetype can specialize another archetype in a manner similar to a subclass in an object-oriented programming environment. Specialized archetypes are, like classes, expressed in a differential form with respect to the parent archetype; i.e., if “Mammal” specializes “Animal,” it may describe lactation, but it would not explicitly repeat the property of heterotrophism. This separation is a necessary pre-requisite to sustainable management of specialized archetypes. An archetype is a specialization of another archetype if it mentions that archetype as its parent, and only makes changes to its definition such that its constraints are ‘narrower’ than those of the parent. Specializations may have further specializations, and the chain of archetypes from a specialized archetype back through all its ancestors is known as an archetype lineage. For a non-specialized (i.e. toplevel) archetype, the lineage is just the archetype itself.

Second, composition permits archetypes to be composed into larger archetypes. Composition allows two things to occur: archetypes can be defined according to natural ‘levels’ or encapsulations of information to assist in analysis and clinical validation, and they can be used by different archetype compositions, facilitating uniformity of approach for clinical information used in different use cases.

There are two mechanisms for expressing composition. First. direct reference allows an archetype to specify a specific archetype to be copied into it. Archetype slots are defined in terms of constraints, allowing any archetype matching the constraint to be applied. Second, the slot pattern, unlike an object model, allows an archetype to have a composition relationship with any number of archetypes matching some constraint pattern. Depending on what archetypes are available within the design system environment at the time the reference is resolved, the archetypes matched may vary.

Archetype flattening

Archetype references may be "dereferenced", where the contents of the referenced archetype(s) are copied into the target "Flat" archetype, resulting in a single, stand-alone collection of constraints. This transformation is referred to as "flattening".

Flattening prepares archetypes for use in systems by dereferencing and making explicit all implicit information. This information includes constraints asserted by parent archetypes in the lineage, archetypes included by composition, and any standard terminology mappings asserted in the Terminology section. Authoring systems will store and operate on un-flattened archetypes in order to take advantage of the scoping and re-use features provided by specialization and composition, but implementers will require the flattened versions.

Archetypes are divided into two classes in the meta-model— SourceArchetype and FlatArchetype—reflecting this operation. Note that, while a SourceArchetype may not reference any other archetype, it is still considered an instance of a SourceArchetype until it is undergoes the flattening process, as implementations may use this process to prune unneeded rules and terminology elements, create local copies of terminological references, etc.

While not represented in this model, AML users frequently talk about the notion of a "template". A template is a flattened archetype designed for implementation.

Note that this implies two very different environments. In the design environment, tools must be able to understand these relationships in order to process archetypes correctly—both by dereferencing ancestor archetypes in the archetype lineage and by including archetypes included by composition. These tools must be able to identify these referenced resources, and they must also be able to access and parse them. The output of this process should be the flat form—the fully explicit artifact ready for implementation. The runtime environment then needs only this single artifact. As noted above, the slot pattern may introduce variation into the precise set of archetypes incorporated into a template if different design environments have access to different sets of source archetypes.

AuthoredResource carries a minimal set of information about the source and origin of an Archetype. Its intent is to be a "connection point" to attach additional workflow and other provenance information to the target Archetype.

Depending on the context and workflow model, it may be possible to update a reference model in a backwards-compatible fashion that doesn't require the referencing archetypes to be revised. rmVersion exists to support this particular situation and records the specific RM version that the archetype was built to constrain.

For any specialized archetype, the archetype it specializes

A FlatArchetype is generated from one or more SourceArchetypes via the flattening process. The flattening operation:

  1. Replaces ComplexObjectConstraintProxies with ComplexObjectConstraints that contain copies of the subtrees to which they point.

  2. Applies SourceArchetype overlays to the parent structure resulting in a full archetype structure.
A flat archetype cannot specialize another archetype

A FlatArchetype is generated from one or more SourceArchetypes via a flattening process described in (currently AOM and ADL spec -- need to transfer). The main changes that occur in the flattening operation are:

  1. Specialized archetype overlays are applied to the flat parent structure, resulting in a full archetype structure.

  2. ComplexObjectConstraintProxies are replaced by their expanded form, i.e. a copy of the subtrees to which they point.

Archetypes can be specialised in a similar way to classes in object-oriented programming languages. Common to both situations is the use of a differential style of declaration, i.e. the contents of a specialised entity are expressed as differences with respect to the parent - previously defined elements from the parent that are not changed are not repeated in the descendant.

The basic test that must be satisfied by a specialised archetype is as follows:

  • All possible data instance arrangements that conform to the specialised archetype must also conform to all of its parents, recursively to the ultimate parent.

This condition ensures that data created by a specialised archetype that is not itself shared by two systems can be processed by the use of a more general parent that is shared.

The semantics that allow this are similar to the ‘covariant redefinition’1 notion used in some object oriented programming languages, and can be summarised as follows:

  • A non-specialised (i.e. top-level) archetype defines an instance space that is a subset of the space defined by the class in the reference information model on which the archetype is based

  • A specialised archetype can specialise only one parent archetype, i.e. single inheritance.

  • A specialised archetype defines an instance space defining the following elements:

    • unchanged object and attribute constraints inherited from the parent archetype;

    • and one or more:

      • redefined object constraints, that are proper subsets of the corresponding parent object constraints;

      • redefined attribute constraints, that are proper subsets of the corresponding parent attribute constraints;

      • extensions, i.e. object constraints added to a container attribute with respect to the corresponding attribute in the parent archetype, but only as allowed by the underlying reference model.

    • All elements defined in a parent archetype are either inherited unchanged or redefined in a specialised child.

    • Specialised archetypes are expressed differentially with respect to the parent, i.e. they do not mention purely inherited elements, only redefinitions and extensions.

    • Extensions always define an additional subset of the instance space defined by the reference model element being extended (i.e. to which the ‘new’ objects belong). The extension capability allows archetypes to remain extensible without having to know in advance how or if they will be extended.

Reference Model Package Overview

This section describes the characteristics a target Reference Model (RM) must have in order for the constraint model to refer to it predictably. These characteristics include:

  1. A known set of axiomatic data types that are common to the Reference Model and the corresponding constraints. If a reference model includes the data type, "complex number", there will be no way to constrain its possible values, ranges, etc. in an archetype without the archetype first knowing its behaviors and characteristics; constraints might, however, be reliably defined on components of that type if it is modeled, e.g., into two reals representing the real and imaginary parts. Similarly, if the reference model defines the (primitive) data type "String" that is represented in UTF-16 and the archetype constraint language represents permissible values in ASCII, it will not be possible to effectively constrain the containing reference model.

  2. A shared set of model artifacts. This constraint model includes tools for constraining data values; it cannot be used to constrain state diagrams or other model artifacts not represented here. Similarly, if the Reference Model makes us of specific OCL constraints, an archetype constraint language cannot be fully validated unless it shares an understanding of the OCL semantics. As an example, if the reference model defines an association with the target cardinality of 0..* and an accompanying OCL constraint restricts it to 0..1, the ACL would have to understand this constraint to recognize that an occurrences constraint of 0..2 was not valid.

  3. A common metamodel. There needs to be a way to explicitly state that an ACL ObjectConstraint constrains an instance of a particular type of class and an AttributeConstraint and instance of a particular property.

The majority of these constraints belong in the Reference Model Profile (RMP) section of this document, as it is the job of a profile to describe the metamodel and its corresponding extensions and restrictions. This section identifies the minimal set of shared primitive types as well as the basic reference model characteristics that must exist in the Reference Model Profile.

The PrimitiveTypes package identifies the set of shared data types that are common between the ReferenceModel, the ConstraintModel, and the Rules packages. This package uses the formal UML notion of "data type" as "a type whose instances are identified only by their value." Data type implementations may include complex structure, but the two instances of the same StringPrimitive or DateTimePrimitive types are identical if their string representations match.

Match patterns have also been included in the primitive section as (a) their model and representation is highly dependent on the target data types and (b) different user communities may want to use different representations and corresponding match pattern representation.

A subset of the UML::Enumeration data type. While UML::Enumeration data types can have both ownedAttributes and ownedOperations, these aspects are ignored from the AML perspective. The only aspects of an RMMEnumeration that are visible in the AML model is the package name.

A RMMEnumerationLiteral is a specialization UML::EnumerationLiteral. The only characteristic that is significant from the AML model perspective is the RMMEnumerationLiteral name, which is unique within the context of the RMMEnumeration namespace. An RMMEnumerationLiteral returns its name as the PermissibleValue value().
A class, in the object-oriented sense
ownedAttribute subsets ownedMember, meaning that the set of RMMProperty names must be unique within the context of the owning RMClass

A Reference Model Property (RMProperty) is a proper subset of a UML property. The aspects of a property that can be addressed by archetype includes:

  1. The property name. Only named properties may be constrained within a reference model. Referring to section 7.4.3 in the ptc/2013-09-05, a non-hidden RMProperty is always referred to in its unqualified form. If it is necessary to reference hidden elements within an archetype, the qualified name (N::x) form should be used. Qualification should be the minimum that sufficient to render the name unique.

  2. The lower and upper bounds. The UML MultiplicityElement shows lower and upper as derived properties. The AML specification assumes that, if present, these properties have been computed and it is up to the implementer to correctly interpret MultiplicityElement lowerValue and upperValue properties to determine these results.

Derived properties cannot be constrained using AML -- the rationale being that (a) derived properties may or may not be present in object instances and (b) the primary constraints need to be applied to the parameters of the derivation rather than the result.

UML::Associations are not used in AML -- the model is traversed via the ownedAttribute association. AssociationClasses are not differentiated from any other RMMClass in the model, and may be referenced and traversed via. whatever ownedAttribute/type links that are available.

While default values can be specified in the Reference Model, they are ignored in AML. Note, however, that AML can specify default values (with tighter semantics) in an archetype.

All other UML::Property links, including aggregation, isComposite, isID, association, qualifier, opposite, defaultVelue, redefines, subsettedProperty, and interface are ignored within the AML profile.
An attribute that is defined in a RMMClass instance.
The RMClass that owns this RMProperty. All RMProperties must be owned by exactly one RMClass.

RMNamedElement is the superclass of all named elements in the Reference Model, and represents the subset of UML::NamedElements that are referenced by the AML profile. While a Reference Model may contain UML::NamedElements without names, Archetypes can only constrain those that have names and are of type RMPrimitiveDataType, RMClass or RMProperty.

RMMDataTypes, like UML::DataTypes "model Types whose instances are distinguished only by their value". RMMDataTypes form the leaf nodes of any AML constraint model -- they are the places where actual atomic value instances are recorded.

While not formally represented in this model (because we don't know how to create a generalization set), the three subclasses of RMMDataType (RMMEnumeration, CompoundRMMDataType and UMLPrimitiveType) are both disjoint and covering.

RMMSingularProperty represents the subset of RMMProperty instances having an upper bound of 1. The AML treats RMMSingular properties as single values (vs. collections) of attributes that can be required, optional or prohibited.

RMMCollectionProperty represents the subset of RMMProperty instances that can occur more than one time. An RMMCollectionProperty instance is viewed by AML as a collection of objects of a given type that possess two separate characteristics:

  1. The collection as a whole may be required, optional or prohibited.

  2. The cardinality of the collection may be constrained.

This combination allows a number of useful constructs, including:

  • requiring that a list be present but that it have no members, which can be used to assert a relationship between an object and an empty set of objects

  • making an attribute optional, but, if present, requiring that it have a minimum number of members

An instance of an instance of an RMClass. As an example, if the RMClass "Automobile" were an instance of an RMClass, with the ownedAttributes "model" and "year", an RMClassInstance might be named "Ford", with the model attribute set to "Fairlane" and the year to "1965".

attribute is an an association that is not present in the UML model itself. It represents the union of the ownedAttributes of the owning RMMClass with the attributes of all superClass RMMClasses. In the case where two or more attribute RMMProperties have the same name, only the most proximal name is visible, and AML cannot address or constrain attributes with the same name in parent or ancestor classes. Note that this (slightly) simplifies the representation of the Template Metamodel.
An RMMEnumeration may own zero or more ownedLiterals of type RMMEnumerationLiteral. Each ownedLiteral is an instance of the containing RMMEnumeration data type.

A RMRedefinableTemplateSignature associates an ordered list of RMClassifierTemplateParameters with an owning RMClass. The owning RMClass typically, but not always has one or more ownedAttributes that reference one of the ownedParameters of the RMRedefinableTemplateSignature.

RMTemplateBinding is a subtype of the UML::TemplateBinding class. It represents a set of parameter substitutions that are to be applied to a RMRedefinableTemplateSignature defined by a parent or ancestor superClass. A RMTemplateBinding contains one or more parameter substitutions to be applied to one or more types referenced by an ownedAttribute of the parent or ancestor class.

A RMTemplateParameterSubstitution indicates that the actual RMClass or RMPrimitiveType is to be substituted as the type for the ownedParameteredElement owned by the formal RMClassifierTemplateParameter.

Quoting the UML 2.5 specification, "A Model is a description of a system, where ‘system’ is meant in the broadest sense and may include not only software and
hardware but organizations and processes. It describes the system from a certain viewpoint (or vantage point) for a certain
category of stakeholders (e.g., designers, users, or customers of the system) and at a certain level of abstraction. A Model is
complete in the sense that it covers the whole system, although only those aspects relevant to its purpose (i.e., within the given
level of abstraction and viewpoint) are represented in the Model."

From the AML perspective, the "aspects relative to [the model's] purpose" consist of a collection of packages which in turn contain a set of RMMClass definitions. To be used in AML, a model must be identified by a unique URI.

Terminology Package Overview

Each archetype has a single Terminology object, which provides definitions for the semantic codes used in the archetype. These codes are found in two kinds of resources: terms and value sets.

Value sets are collections of coded values that can be used in constraints, e.g., a disease that must be represented by a value from a subset of SNOMED CT. The value set may consist of terms enumerated explicitly in the archetype, or it may reference an externally defined value set that can be accessed using a terminology service—or it may do both.

Terms are coded values. Codes are used for two reasons. First, human language descriptions can be ambiguous, especially when used outside the context in which they are written. The use of a code ensures that the intent is unambiguous by providing a standard reference for defining the value and removing the need to invent language that may or may not reflect the same semantics in different circumstances.

Second, archetypes may provide human-language descriptions of concepts in many languages. The archetype uses the non-semantic code to refer to the concept, and the tools used to view or implement the archetype allow the user to select the preferred language for display.

These coded semantic identifiers are used for two purposes. They make up the concepts used in value sets to support constraint definitions. And they serve as node identifiers that name branches of the graph (complete blood count panel, serum sodium observation, etc.). In this way, not only the coded primitive values but the structures of the archetype are semantically fixed.

A permissible value within the context of a value domain. While permissible values may be represented as integers, strings or simply as named data type instances (as is the case in UML), all permissible values need to have a mechanism for providing a String representation of the represented value. The String returned by the value function must be unique within the context of the containing domain.

An EnumeratedValueDomain represents a discrete set of possible values for a particular field or data element. Each permissible value represents an intended meaning that, while sometimes determinable from the string itself or its accompanying documentation, can only be fully fixed by connecting it to an official "value meaning" reference in an external terminological resource.
The set of valid or "permissible" values for the particular domain.

Constraint Model Package Overview

The constraint model is the core of the archetype design. It illustrates how constraints are defined, showing the object-attribute-object pattern characteristic of object constraints.

The constraint model is designed to be generic, and to express the semantics of constraints on instances of classes which are themselves described in UML or any similar object-oriented meta-model). Accordingly, the major abstractions in this model correspond to major abstractions in object-oriented formalisms, including several variations of the notion of ‘object’ and the notion of ‘attribute’. The notion of ‘object’ rather than ‘class’ or ‘type’ is used because archetypes are about constraints on data (i.e. ‘instances’, or ‘objects’) rather than models, which are constructed from ‘classes’. In this document, the word ‘attribute’ refers to any data property of a class, regardless of whether regarded as a ‘relationship’(i.e. association, aggregation, or composition) or ‘primitive’ (i.e. value) attribute in an object model.

 The definition part of an archetype is an instance of a ComplexObjectConstraint. Because objects are composed of properties (attributes and relationships), and properties consist of objects, the archetype definition consists of alternate layers of object and attribute constrainer nodes, each containing the next level of nodes. At the leaves are primitive object constrainer nodes constraining primitive types such as String, Integeretc.

There are also nodes that refer to other nodes within the archetype, nodes that refer to text constraints in the constraint binding part of the archetype terminology, and nodes that accommodate the incorporation of externally defined archetypes at the node.

 The full list of concrete node types is as follows:

  • ComplexObjectConstraint: a node representing a constraint on instances of some nonprimitive reference model type

  • AttributeConstraint: a node representing a constraint on an attribute (i.e. UML ‘relationship’ or

  • ‘primitive attribute’) in an object type

  • PrimitiveObjectConstraint: a node representing a constraint on a primitive (built-in) object type

  • ComplexObjectConstraintProxy: a node that refers to a previously defined object constraint node in the same archetype. The reference is made using a path.

  • ArchetypeRootConstraint: a node that refers to another archetype, enabling it to be incorporated by reference.

  • ArchetypeSlot: a node whose statements define a constraint on archetypes, determining which other archetypes can appear at that point in the current archetype. It is similar to an ArchetypeRootConstraint, but rather than a single archetype, it defines a set of archetypes. It can be thought of like a keyhole, into which few or many keys might fit, depending on how specific its shape is. Logically it has the same semantics as a ComplexObjectConstraint, except that the constraints are expressed in another archetype, not the current one.

The constraints define criteria by which reference model class instances can be judged to conform to or depart from the archetype. For example, certain configurations of the openEHR reference model classes PARTY, ADDRESS, CLUSTER and ELEMENT might be defined by a Person archetype as allowable structures for ‘people with identity, contacts, and addresses’. Because the constraints allow optionality, cardinality and other choices, a given archetype usually corresponds to a set of similar configurations of objects.

ComplexObjectConstraints

It is unlikely that different reference models would define domain classes identically. ComplexObjectConstraints, then, do not address the object values directly, but rather by constraining the values of the attributes that compose them. A constraint on the Person class has no option but to constrain by parts: it might require a property (e.g., address), or require several, or prohibit some property.

PrimitiveObjectConstraints

The exception to that rule is at the lower threshold of the information modeling paradigm, where objects are either undefined or defined by some external specification. The Boolean values True and False cannot be decomposed, and the String type can be implemented in a number of ways, none of which is relevant to the design of content constraints. It is at this level that the constraint model engages the reference model directly. A constraint on Boolean values must specify the values in the same way that the reference model does. A set of valid Strings to match instances against must use the same primitive type as the reference model.

AttributeConstraints

Like object constraints, attribute constraints do not address attribute values directly, instead specifying three things:

  • The name of the reference model attribute being constrained

  • Existence, or whether an attribute may or may not be present

  • Negation, or whether the pattern described in the contained object constraint is to be matched or must not be matched

Single attributes are modeled with the SingularAttributeConstraint class. Where a SingularAttributeConstraint  is associated with more than one ObjectConstraint, the ObjectConstraints are alternatives.

Attributes with multiple values are modeled with the AttributeCollectionConstraint, which differentiates between unique and repeatable and between ordered and unordered collections. In addition, while the AttributeConstraint determines whether a property may exist, the quantity of a repeating element is defined in the AttributeCollectionConstraint’s cardinality property.

There is one further numeric constraint: within such an AttributeCollectionConstraint, with its defined cardinality, there may be different sets of sibling members with different constraints, and the number of each of these subsets is specified as the AttributeCollectionMember’s occurrences property. In an organization, for instance, the cardinality for the member property may be “two or more,” but within that set of members, we may have two constraints. One type of member, the leader (indicated by an ObjectConstraint on the person type or role), may be required to occur exactly once, whereas other types may have multiple occurrences.

AttributeTupleConstraints

Tuples are used to couple related constraints. Blood pressure readings, for instance, might be capped at 400 (a number believed to be clinically impossible and therefore indicative of a system error) when recorded in mmHg, but would have a different criterion for atmospheres, pascals, or cmH2O. In this case, an AttributeTuple would be defined for each pair of the two values (unit code and numeric ceiling), and these tuples would be grouped into an AttributeTupleConstraint, defining an array of acceptable sets of values.

Primitive constraints constitute the foundation of the constraint architecture, as they constrain the values that more complex types carry. Ultimately, any archetype definition will devolve down to leaf node constraints on instances of primitive types. The primitive package defines the semantics of constraint on such types.

ObjectConstraint represents the properties and associations that are common to all types of object constraints:

  1. Every object constraint may directly specialize at most one parent ObjectConstraint

  2. Every AttributeConstraint is owned by exactly one ObjectConstraint

  3. Every ObjectConstraint is referenced by exactly one AttributeConstraint, with the exception of the root Archetype definition ComplexObjectConstraint that is not owned by any referencing attribute.

The subtypes of ObjectConstraint include:

  1. ObjectConstraintProxy - a reference to an existing NamedObjectConstraint. ObjectConstraintProxys only exist in SourceArchetypes and are replaced by a copy of their targetObject during the flattening process.

  2. NamedObjectConstraint - the set of ObjectConstraints that reference a Reference Model Class and have node identifiers

    1. EnumerationConstraint - constraints on the Reference Model Enumeration class

    2. ArchetypeSlot - identifies a (constrained) slot to be filled by a separate archetype

    3. ArchetypeRootProxy - references an archetype that constraints the type and/or attributes of a Reference Model Class and optionally fills an ArchetypeSlot defined in a parent Archetype

    4. ComplexObjectConstraint - a constraint on the type and/or attributes of a Reference Model Class

  3. TerminologyConstraint - constraints on the TerminologyCodeReference type

  4. PrimitiveObjectConstraint - constraints on the set of primitive data types supplied in the reference model
